Japan, Australia Stock Futures Drop on U.S. Jobless Claims, Spain Rating

-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 
2011-03-10T23:06:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-10/japan-australia-stock-futures-drop-on-u-s-jobless-claims-spain-rating.html
Japanese and Australian stock
futures declined after more Americans filed jobless claims
and  Spain ’s credit rating was downgraded, stoking concern that
the economic recovery may falter.  American depositary receipts of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial
Group Inc., Japan’s biggest publicly traded bank, sank 1.7
percent from the closing share price in Tokyo. Those of Toyota
Motor Corp., the world’s No. 1 carmaker, slid 0.6 percent. ADRs
of National  Australia  Bank Ltd., Australia’s fourth-largest
lender, lost 1.2 percent in Sydney.  “After a period of optimism, there are now all of these
concerns,” said Juichi Wako, a senior strategist at Tokyo-based
Nomura Holdings Inc. “Exporters should lead declines” because
of the deterioration in U.S. economic data and Spain’s downgrade.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
June closed at 10,275 in  Chicago  yesterday, compared with 10,370
in Osaka. Futures on Australia’s S&P/ASX 200 Index declined 0.8
percent in Sydney.  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index fell 0.2 percent
today. The index dropped 1.9 percent yesterday in  New York ,
after the U.S. Labor Department said applications for first-time  unemployment benefits  rose by 26,000 to 397,000 in the week
ended March 5. Economists forecast claims would climb to 376,000,
according to the median estimate in a Bloomberg News survey.  Spain Downgrade  Separately, the U.S. Commerce Department said the deficit
in goods and services increased 15 percent to $46.3 billion in
January as a surge in imports led by costlier crude oil
overshadowed record exports.  In  Europe , Spain’s credit rating was cut to Aa2 by Moody’s
Investors Service, which said the cost of shoring up the banking
industry will eclipse government estimates.  Crude oil for April delivery declined 1.6 percent to settle
at $102.70 a barrel in New York yesterday, after falling as much
as 3.6 percent earlier. Oil pared losses after the police in  Saudi Arabia , the Middle East’s biggest producer of crude,
reportedly opened fire at a rally in the east of the country.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index fell 1.1 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with gains of 3 percent by the S&P
500 and 0.8 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Shares in the
Asian benchmark were valued at 13.9 times estimated earnings on
average as of the last close, compared with 13.4 times for the
S&P 500 and 11.1 times for the Stoxx 600.  To contact the reporters on this story:
